    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="abstract">
                <p tid="1">A collection of 245 short liturgies translated by Trakpa Gyaltsen (Toh 3400-3644)</p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="article">
                <head type="article" tid="5">Ocean of Sādhanas</head>
                <div type="section" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21626-article-1">
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21626-1"/>
                    <p tid="2">A distinct collection of 245 short sādhanas, centered on a wide range of deities and known as the <title xml:lang="en">Ocean of Sādhanas</title> (<title xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">sgrub thabs rga mtsho</title>, or
                            <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Sādhanasāgara</title>, also known as <title xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">sgrub thabs kun
                            las btus pa</title>, or <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Sādhanasamuccaya</title> ).</p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21626-2"/>
                    <p tid="3">All 245 works were translated at Sakya in 1286 by Yarlung Lotsāwa Trakpa Gyaltsen 
                        (<foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">yar klungs lo tsA ba grags pa rgyal mtshan</foreign>, 1242–1346), who received the transmission from “the
                        great paṇḍita Gautama” through the “great paṇḍita Kīrticandra.”</p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21626-3"/>
                    <p tid="4">The collection is closely related to a collection of sādhanas in Sanskrit found in two manuscripts of the
                        12th and 13th centuries, known as the <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Sādhanamāla</title> (Bhattacaryya, B.,
                        Baroda, 1925).</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </body>
